            "content": "&#128218; &nbsp;The Präsens tense"
        },
        {
            "type": "h2-post",
            "content": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "The <b><i>Präsens</i></b> tense in German direclty corresponds to the present tense in English. It is mostly used to describe actions that are happening right now or habitual actions. </br>However, it is also frequently used to describe future actions or actions happenning now with continuation on the  future. This is because in German the future tense is rarely used and there is no present continuous tense. The <i>Präsens</i> should be the first tense to learn when starting to learn German."
        },
        {
            "type": "callout",
            "content": "With the <i>Präsens</i>, you are getting 3 tenses in one: <strong>present</strong>, <strong>present continuous</strong> and <strong>future</strong>! &nbsp;&nbsp; &#127881"
        },
        {
            "type": "h2",
            "content": "Usage"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "We use the <i>Präsens</i> tense to express:"
        },
        {
            "type": "list",
            "itemsList": {
                "items": [
                    {
                        "text": "<b>Present Actions:</b> Describing actions happening in the present.",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Ich lese ein Buch.",
                            "text": "Example: Ich $__lese-lesen[verb-link-hover]__$ ein Buch.",
                            "translation": "(I am reading a book.)"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "<b>Habitual Actions:</b> Expressing routine or habitual actions.",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Ich trinke jeden Morgen Kaffee.",
                            "text": "Example: Ich $__trinke-trinken[verb-link-hover]__$ jeden Morgen Kaffee.",
                            "translation": "(I drink coffee every morning.)"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "<b>General Truths:</b> Stating facts or general truths.",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Die Erde is rund.",
                            "text": "Example: Die Erde $__ist-sein[verb-link-hover]__$ rund.",
                            "translation": "(The Earth ist round.)"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "<b>Actions already started and still happening:</b> In english we would use the present perfect tense: 'He has been playing...'.",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Er arbeitet seit 3 monate ins Kino.",
                            "text": "Example: Er $__arbeitet-arbeiten[verb-link-hover]__$ seit 3 monate ins Kino.",
                            "translation": "(He has been working in the cinema for 3 months.)"
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "h2",
            "content": "Conjugation"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "The conjugation rules differ among <b>regular</b> verbs, which always follow the same rules; a few <b>irregular verbs</b>, which must be memorized individually; and <b>stem-vowel-changing</b> irregular verbs, which have slight modifications compared to the regular ones."
        },
